title: For Sale:  Inron MY803 "Poor Man's Hinderer" Black EDC Folding Knife NEW
location: Ships anywhere in CONUS, Las Vegas, Nevada
postcontent:
- USA Based Dealer -

NEWLY ARRIVED 
Inron MY803 Folding EDC Pocket Knife w/Black G10 Handle
"Poor Man's Hinderer"

As a knife enthusiast, you may be "in the know" about the high quality yet low cost Sanrenmu, Enlan, and Ganzo knives. 

These little known knife manufacturers are credited with making some very high quality, well designed yet affordable folder knives especially well suited for every day carry purposes. In fact if you have any contacts within the knife/cutlery trade you will find out that Ganzo, Sanrenmu and Enlan's other activities include manufacturing knives for numerous western brands such as Benchmande, Spyderco, Buck, and SOG. So believe me when I say you're getting a lot for your money with these guys.

Now there's a new name to add to this list of quality folders. Enter Inron Cutlery with there beautifully made model MY803, aka "the poor man's Hinderer" so called for its strikingly similar design to that of the Rick Hinderer XM18. Of course this is comparing apples to very expensive oranges but you still get a similar look and ergonomic feel for the price of an XM18 washer.

The MY803 is a good sized folder at 8.8" in total length with a 3.85" high hollow ground blade. The blade steel is a 9Cr13MoV which is similar to 440C steel (more so than the older 8Cr13Mov is). This is a framelock knife with "flipper" action as well as ambidextrous thumb studs. 

I would say the MY803 has an excellent fit and finish for the price. Good detent, very solid lock up without any blade play. It has a flat head pivot screw for easy adjustments and it's ergonomic, oversized handle (easily used with a gloved hand) is made from G10 and is available in 3 color options. 

This solid knife weighs in at 5.6oz using drilled steel liners for weight reduction. For a larger EDC knife, the very slim profile design carries surprisingly well in the pocket. It comes tip up and right hand carry only.


Knife Specs:

Blade Length: 3.9" 
Cutting Edge: 3.5
Blade Thickness: 3.6mm
Blade Steel: 9Cr13MoV Stainless Steel Hollow Ground (59-60HRC)
Open Length: 8.8"
Closed Length: 5"
Weight: 5.6oz 
Handle: Black G-10/Steel w/Spine Jimping
Handle Thickness: 10.5mm
Lock: Frame Lock
Opening Mechanism: Flipper with Ambidextrous Thumb Studs
Carry: Right Hand Tip Up w/Lanyard Hole

Included in the box are 2 .308 Magpul PMAGS, manual, chamber flag, and all the usual stuff that comes with rifles nowadays. The serial number on this firearm numbers under 400, a little factiod that I think is pretty cool. I had my eyes on one of these rifles for a while now, but circumstances have changed and I figure that this rifle can find a happy home out there somewhere. I am asking $2,800 for it, and of course I am really only interested in selling the firearm to Illinois residents that possess a FOID card.
I am also throwing in my old scope, which is a Blackhawk brand 3-9x40mm scope with a mil-dot reticle, adjustable for windage and elevation in 1/10th mil increments. It has a one inch tube, mounting hardware is not included here. This is a used optic in great condition, I'm selling it because the rifle it was on now has a scope with more magnification than this one offered. For anyone who is interested, the story on these scopes is that they were sold only at Cabelas, they were made in Japan, and by most accounts I have come across they appear to be re-branded Nikon scopes with a Blackhawk! tag slapped on them. It was a great scope for me, and it fits the look of the .308 upper very well. 

I should probably mention that yes, this is the rifle that will accept 5.56mm uppers; however, the special magazine well insert is an item that is sold separately from the rifle. I do not own the insert, and as such that part is not included in the deal. Sorry, as it turns out Colt makes 901 owners buy that little part on their own. 
I am willing to take off some of the price if anyone out there has a good condition German Mauser (K98) or Springfield XDm (9mm) to offer up.

Some guy stops you at a light or in a parking lot usually driving a white van and tells you that he has this leftover merchandise that his boss dosen't know about and he will sell it to you at a fraction of the cost printed on the box.  It is a scam look it up.  I'm sorry you got ripped off but don't perpetuate the scam onto others.  All white van speaker company's have their own web sites , how else would you scam someone with a smartphone.

title: For Sale/Trade:  German ERMA-WERKE Baby Luger 4” Barrel .22LR
postcontent:
For those Collectors or Weekend Warriors that can’t afford the Thousands for an original P08 German made Luger or have researched the Inherent Problems of the U.S. Manufactured Stoeger Lugers I have an Alternative.
This West German made Erma is the only one currently listed on Armslist Nationwide, and may very well be the Only One in the State of Colorado.
Read the information below to understand why this is such a Rare German Made Pistol. 

The Erma-Werke Luger Model KGP-69 is a Toggle Locked, Blowback Operated Pistol that is Chambered in .22 Cal.LR.  It has a Steel Receiver, Toggle Train and Barrel (1/2" shorter than the P08). The lower Frame seems to be a steel alloy. The Steel Receiver and Barrel Assembly is Blued; (Bluish-Black). Lower Frame has a black coating. The grip panels are molded synthetic in a Simulated Wood Design..
The Company started After the Soviets burned the Lugar factory, using some of the same Tooling Equipment and Manpower. Known as Erfurter Maschinen und Werkzeugfabrik, the facility moved to Munich-Dachau Germany and became known as Erma-Werke.
Prior to WWII Erma produced the .22cal Conversion kit for the 9mm P08 Luger Pistol and was so successful that Erma decided to manufacture its own small target pistol. From the first .22 made in 1936 known as the Old Model; to 1969 and the first KGP-69 it has incorporated the improvements of its Predecessors including its pure blowback design.  Erma-Werke went out of business in 1997. 
I purchased this Firearm New in 1976 and have put less than 100 rounds down the pipe. Internally it’s a New Pistol. Always been a sweet gentle Plinker. Would look great with some Beeman Walnut  Grips. Comes with Owners Manual and takedown instructions as well as original factory Eight Round Magazine. Be the first one on the range to fire this Great Looking Luger at a Fraction of the cost of Ammo.   Make me an Offer or lets Trade
